3. Evaluating ACF and PACF plots

ACF plot shows the significant correlation between current time series and previous lags. Typically, such assumption is appropriate when time series, represented by vertical lines, cross the level of significance (blue dashed line) just as it dispalys. Also, observation suggests presence of correlation between the last 3 terms, which makes the lag possibly equal to 3. Since time series drop gradually, there is an assumption of non-stationary data behavior. Versus, if there was a sudden drop it would point on the stationary data and zero correlation between lags.
PACF also suggests lag equal to 3, because of the first three vertical lines, that are above the 95% of significance level.
To verify above assumptions, adf.test() is performed. Null hypothesis is that data is non-stationary. Since p-value is 0.144 which is more then excepted 0.05, we fail to reject null hypothesis and have enough evidence to assume that the data is non-stationary. Adf.test() also recommends lag of 3, which confirms findings from the plots.

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
# Modeling time series against Invoice Values per plots ACF
# and PACF
acf(as.ts(dataset[13:50, ]$TotalInv), main = "Sales")  #excluded years 2020 [52:54,] and 2016
pacf(as.ts(dataset[13:50, ]$TotalInv), main = "Sales")

par(mfrow = c(1, 1))

tseries::adf.test(TotalInv[13:50], alternative = "stationary")
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  TotalInv[13:50]
## Dickey-Fuller = -3.0986, Lag order = 3, p-value =
## 0.144
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

4.Considering Exponential Smoothening with Additive and Multiplicative types

Decomposed data look very similar.

    1))
dataset_ts <- window(ts_hw, start = c(2017, 1), end = c(2019, 
    10))

### 5. Using the Winter-Holts method to predict sales

Decomposed plots above showed an increase in trend and steady seasonality. This suggests that more appropriate type would be an additive type.

fit1 <- hw(dataset_ts, seasonal = "additive")
fit2 <- hw(dataset_ts, seasonal = "multiplicative")
autoplot(dataset_ts) + autolayer(fit1, series = "HW additive forecast", 
    PI = FALSE) + autolayer(fit2, series = "HW multiplicative forecast", 
    PI = FALSE)

plot(forecast(fit1, 12))

lines(fitted(fit1), col = "red")
lines(ts_hw, col = "black")

fit1$model
